ns that often determined the fate of men. That some of these decisions were capricious or even wrong is indisputable; the sparse historiography of the Tribunals has too often focused upon the idiosyncratic example while ignoring the wider, impact of imprecise legislation, government hand-washing and short-term military exigencies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCourts-martial and courts of inquiryzGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aDraftzGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aMilitary Service Tribunals.  aWhitehall.  aapplications for exemption.  aarmy.  aconscription.  acontradictions.  alegislation.  apower.  asocial dynamics.  asovereign body.1 aMcDermott, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978184779418540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847794185423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847794185/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles